{"summary":"Both amendments describe real correctness defects in milestone completion handling: one makes partial-write failures non-recoverable, and the other persists a snapshot state the model explicitly defines as inconsistent.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-3-b8dbc656","decision":"accept","rationale":"`update_task_run` finalizes the lineage entry before writing `status.json` or appending the journal event, and `FsTaskRunLineageStore::update_task_run` rejects any attempt to finalize an already-terminal row. That means a transient failure in `write_snapshot` or `append_event` leaves lineage ahead of the other milestone artifacts, and a retry of the same completion cannot repair the drift through the normal API. I could not find any milestone-specific reconcile path that rebuilds snapshot or journal from lineage, so this is a real durability and idempotence bug."},{"amendment_id":"fr-3-9fecdf73","decision":"accept","rationale":"`record_bead_start` promotes the milestone to `MilestoneStatus::Active`, but completion only decrements counters and clears `active_bead` when it matches the completed bead. It does not transition `status` away from `Active` or validate semantics before persisting. `MilestoneSnapshot::validate_semantics` explicitly rejects `status == Active && active_bead == None`, and `write_snapshot` does not enforce that invariant, so the normal start-then-complete flow can write an internally inconsistent snapshot."}]}